column2: An insurance policy is a contract of "Utmost Good Faith (Uberrimae Fidei)" which requires you to voluntarily disclose to the insurer(s) all material facts (any circumstance/information that would influence the insurer(s) in setting the premium or deciding whether or not to accept the risks proposed) that you know or could reasonably be expected to know.

column2: If you fail to comply with your duty of disclosure, the insurer may be entitled to reduce its liability under the contract in respect of a claim or to cancel the contract. If your disclosure is fraudulent, the insurer may have the right to cancel the policy ab initio.
